n marginal landscapes.Informing its literary investigations with relevant concerns from economic history, patristic doctrine and decision theory, the volume offers a comprehensive new look at the psychology of landscape and season in medieval literature; it also brings out beliefs concerning the seasons and their connections with the supernatural. Paul S. Langeslag is a lecturer of Medieval English Studies at the University of Göttingen, Germany.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismyMiddle English, 1100-1500. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismyOld English, ca. 450-1100. 0aOld Norse literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aSeasons in literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChanging seasons.  aEconomic history.  aFigurative Functions.  aFigurative functions.  aLandscape.  aMarginal Landscapes.  aMaterial Realities.  aMaterial realities.  aMedieval Literature.  aMedieval literature.  aMyth.  aNorthwestern Europe.  aPsychology of landscape.  aPsychology.  aRitual Calendars.  aSeasonal Settings.  aSeasons.  aSociety.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782045847?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782045847423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782045847/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles